<div class="problem-container section" id="problem">
  <div class="problem">
    <div class="problem-text1">
      <h1>PROBLEM</h1><br />
      <p>
        Companies split up into multiple subteams generally show a decrease in interaction and collaboration with one another.  It's like having a bunch of small mini companies within one big company.  You lose knowledge transfer from one team to the next.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="chart-container">
      <canvas id="turnOver"></canvas>
    </div>
    <div class="problem-text2">
      <p>
        When companies get bigger, you generally don't get to know everyone.  So when you're stumped with a problem, it's hard to know who to ask... you know someone out there can help you, but who exactly?
      </p>
      <br />
      <p>
        You also tend to cross paths with many personalities throughout the day.  Obviously some personalities are easier to work with than others.  It can be tough to communicate with THAT person directly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="solution-container section" id="solution">
  <div class="solution">
    <div class="solution-text">
      <h1>SOLUTION</h1><br />
      <p>
        TeamChat is a messaging application with an anonymous feature that can solve these issues.  The application allows you to set an optional screenname to hide your identity, otherwise you are made known in one-on-one conversations.<br /><br />

        The idea is to organize channels in groups that would be helpful.  This would probably be most applicable to large teams such as engineering teams.  A company may have 50 engineers split up into 8 smaller individual teams.  It would be beneficial to have 1 channel with all 50 engineers in one so that questions and problems can pool on the knowledge of the entire team rather than just subteams.  Thus inducing more collaboration and interaction which would increase efficiency and employee satisfaction.<br /><br />

        Interns, new employees, and anyone really would be able to have their problems and questions answered in seconds and team unification would become stronger as a result!
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="stats">
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
